<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="556" pageId="5" pageNumber="555" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1963,2026]" lastBlockId="6.[151,1437,151,538]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="556" pageId="5" pageNumber="555">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1963,1989]" pageId="5" pageNumber="555">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The only species of the 
<emphasis box="[572,650,1963,1989]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="555">tibialis</emphasis>
group with the following combination of characters: Females with spinose femora, legs yellow with the distal 1/3 of hind femur and apex of hind tibia dark brown; wing with distal portion of costa and radius curved, elongate (costal ratio 0.89–0.91). Males with elongate genitalia that are tilted dorsally 45°, parameres divided with recurved tips bearing minute spicules (
<figureCitation box="[1005,1094,187,214]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[286,1311,198,1907]" captionTargetId="figure-19@8.[264,1324,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Female abdomens (A, C−D) and male genitalia (B). A. Palpomyia aspina, dorsal view; B. P. subaspera, male genitalia, ventral view; C−D. P. auakua sp. nov., ventral view. Scale bars: A, C= 0.5 mm; B, D= 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5224045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5224045/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="556">Fig. 6B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="556" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,538]" pageId="6" pageNumber="556">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,223,249]" pageId="6" pageNumber="556">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species is widely distributed in the Nearctic and Neotropical regions. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Grogan, W. L. Jr. &amp; Wirth, W. W." pageId="6" pageNumber="556" pagination="1 - 125" refId="ref5432" refString="Grogan, W. L. Jr. &amp; Wirth, W. W. (1979) The North American predaceous midges of the genus Palpomyia Meigen (Diptera: Ceratopogonidae). Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Washington, 8, i - vi, + 1 - 125." type="journal article" year="1979">Grogan &amp; Wirth (1979)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Spinelli, G. R. &amp; Grogan, W. L. Jr. &amp; Ronderos, M. M." box="[355,593,259,285]" pageId="6" pageNumber="556" pagination="43 - 70" refId="ref5925" refString="Spinelli, G. R., Grogan, W. L. Jr. &amp; Ronderos, M. M. (2009) A revision of the Patagonian predaceous midges of the genus Palpomyia Meigen (Diptera: Ceratopogonidae). Insect Systematics &amp; Evolution, 40, 43 - 70. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631209 X 416705" type="journal article" year="2009">
Spinelli 
<emphasis box="[450,501,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="556">et al</emphasis>
. (2009)
</bibRefCitation>
, males fore femur with 2-4 spines and the gonocoxite lacks a mesoventral lobe. However, in the specimens from 
<collectingRegion box="[582,685,295,321]" country="Mexico" name="Veracruz de Ignacio de la Llave" pageId="6" pageNumber="556">Veracruz</collectingRegion>
, we observed that the fore femur lacks ventral spines and the gonocoxite has a small distal mesoventral lobe (
<figureCitation box="[633,722,331,358]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[286,1311,198,1907]" captionTargetId="figure-19@8.[264,1324,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Female abdomens (A, C−D) and male genitalia (B). A. Palpomyia aspina, dorsal view; B. P. subaspera, male genitalia, ventral view; C−D. P. auakua sp. nov., ventral view. Scale bars: A, C= 0.5 mm; B, D= 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5224045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5224045/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="556">Fig. 6B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
